00:00:00.305 --> 00:00:01.500
MALE SPEAKER: Hi, everyone.

00:00:01.500 --> 00:00:05.280
Welcome to another Authors
at Google Talk.

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:07.240
We're have to have DC
Pierson with us.

00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:10.280
First time I met him, he was
doing improv at the Upright

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:12.420
Citizens Brigade theater.

00:00:12.420 --> 00:00:14.660
And then I found out he had a
host of other things that he

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:17.170
did, which is write books.

00:00:17.170 --> 00:00:21.050
He wrote and starred in a
independent movie that he did

00:00:21.050 --> 00:00:23.990
as part of his comedy troupe.

00:00:23.990 --> 00:00:26.410
And so we're very excited
to have him today.

00:00:26.410 --> 00:00:27.410
DC Pierson.

00:00:27.410 --> 00:00:27.990
DC PIERSON: Hey, guys.

00:00:27.990 --> 00:00:28.670
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:28.670 --> 00:00:29.920
DC PIERSON: Hey.

00:00:32.590 --> 00:00:33.180
How's it going?

00:00:33.180 --> 00:00:34.990
Thanks for coming out.

00:00:34.990 --> 00:00:38.080
So my name is DC Pierson.

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:40.060
I wrote a book called "The Boy
Who Couldn't Sleep and Never

00:00:40.060 --> 00:00:45.890
Had To." And then actually next
Thursday, March 7, my new

00:00:45.890 --> 00:00:47.400
book is coming out.

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:50.410
It's called "Crap Kingdom," and
I wanted to talk a little

00:00:50.410 --> 00:00:53.970
bit about that, and a little bit
about the process of being

00:00:53.970 --> 00:00:57.770
a writer while also doing a
bunch of other things and

00:00:57.770 --> 00:01:02.100
hopefully be funny and
or interesting.

00:01:02.100 --> 00:01:06.400
I'd rather be funny
than informative.

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:08.060
Hopefully I'll be one or
the other, though.

00:01:08.060 --> 00:01:13.120
So my book "Crap Kingdom" is a
young adult comedic fantasy

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:16.760
adventure about a kid who loves
Chronicles of Narnia, he

00:01:16.760 --> 00:01:19.940
loves Harry Potter, he loves
basically anything where

00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:24.530
there's a kid in the normal
world and he gets taken to a

00:01:24.530 --> 00:01:27.340
crazy magical fantasy realm
where he gets told, you're the

00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:29.920
chosen one, in this crazy
magical fantasy realm.

00:01:29.920 --> 00:01:32.240
And then that actually happens
to our main character.

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:34.940
He gets taken to a crazy magical
fantasy realm from our

00:01:34.940 --> 00:01:36.960
world, where he's told,
you're the chosen one.

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:39.850
It just turns out that the crazy
magical fantasy realm in

00:01:39.850 --> 00:01:43.920
which he's the chosen one is
really, really crappy.

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:49.580
And so it's kind of a book,
among other things, about

00:01:49.580 --> 00:01:51.610
trying to exist in two worlds.

00:01:51.610 --> 00:01:55.490
Because he kind of likes
his life on Earth.

00:01:55.490 --> 00:01:56.520
He thinks it's OK.

00:01:56.520 --> 00:02:00.020
He thinks it's maybe too OK, and
the fact that it's so OK

00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:02.840
means that he'll never be taken
to another world and

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:04.420
told he's the chosen one.

00:02:04.420 --> 00:02:06.290
And when that actually happens
to him, and the world in which

00:02:06.290 --> 00:02:08.440
he's the chosen one is really
crappy, he's like, maybe I

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:10.169
don't want to do this.

00:02:10.169 --> 00:02:11.950
Maybe I just want to go back
to the real world.

00:02:11.950 --> 00:02:14.710
Maybe I wasn't fully
appreciating it or whatever.

00:02:14.710 --> 00:02:16.890
And that's kind of a little
bit what I wanted to talk

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:21.930
about in my own life, and kind
of my own journey, if you want

00:02:21.930 --> 00:02:26.190
to pretentiously call it that,
with trying to exist in

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:27.830
multiple worlds.

00:02:27.830 --> 00:02:30.930
So part of the premise of my
book, and I think also part of

00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:33.240
the premise of most fantasy
literature--

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:37.190
I don't know if there's any
people who have been or are

00:02:37.190 --> 00:02:39.460
fans of fantasy literature
in here.

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:41.190
I figured it was a
pretty safe bet.

00:02:44.330 --> 00:02:48.340
But it feels like in fantasy
literature--

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:52.940
like things in science fiction
or things in real life, they

00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:54.630
take place in a universe.

00:02:54.630 --> 00:02:58.120
And universes are bound by
physical laws and science, and

00:02:58.120 --> 00:03:00.540
they have actual boundaries.

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:03.850
And if you're an avid "Radio
Lab" listener the way I am,

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:06.110
apparently there's multiple
universes, and they're

00:03:06.110 --> 00:03:08.050
expanding like soap bubbles
or something.

00:03:08.050 --> 00:03:09.750
I don't really remember.

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:11.330
I just thought it was very
interesting while I was

00:03:11.330 --> 00:03:13.090
folding laundry and I was like,
hmm, this really changes

00:03:13.090 --> 00:03:13.540
everything.

00:03:13.540 --> 00:03:17.510
And it did, but I don't remember
anything about it.

00:03:17.510 --> 00:03:23.230
But in fantasy literature, it's
almost like instead of

00:03:23.230 --> 00:03:25.370
universes, we have worlds.

00:03:25.370 --> 00:03:27.360
We have that thing that's in the
front of the book that's

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:28.340
like the map.

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:30.710
It's like Middle Earth or
Narnia or whatever.

00:03:30.710 --> 00:03:34.740
And worlds seem to be, instead
of like universes being bound

00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:40.890
by like actual hard physical
science, worlds kind of seem

00:03:40.890 --> 00:03:43.810
to be held together
more by vibe.

00:03:43.810 --> 00:03:45.430
Like when you go to Middle
Earth, you know you're in

00:03:45.430 --> 00:03:45.980
Middle Earth.

00:03:45.980 --> 00:03:48.310
When you go to Narnia, you know
you're in Narnia, because

00:03:48.310 --> 00:03:51.840
everything represents things
from the Bible.

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:53.740
That's what I love about
fantasy literature--

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:58.010
is that instead of these very
sort of hard, bound by

00:03:58.010 --> 00:04:01.680
physics, soap bubble universes
that are constantly expanding,

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:05.470
you have worlds that are
connected by a wardrobe, or a

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:12.150
portal, or in my case in "Crap
Kingdom," a Goodwill donation

00:04:12.150 --> 00:04:15.190
box in the parking
lot of a Kmart.

00:04:15.190 --> 00:04:17.769
That should've been his
first clue, actually.

00:04:17.769 --> 00:04:22.900
And I like, and have liked for
many years, as a person and as

00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:27.050
an artist, enjoyed existing in
a lot of different worlds.

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:29.830
Because in addition to
being an author, an

00:04:29.830 --> 00:04:31.520
actor, I'm a comedian--

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:34.720
I started in sketch and then
studied improv and now I do

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:36.820
stand up as well.

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:38.290
I'm in commercials.

00:04:38.290 --> 00:04:41.210
You may have seen me trying to
sell you Allstate Insurance,

00:04:41.210 --> 00:04:42.520
which I'm sure is fine.

00:04:45.028 --> 00:04:48.080
I have Geico.

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:50.000
But anyway, it's
not important.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.010
Dennis Haysbert's so mad
at me right now.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:05:02.070
So I've liked being the funny
comedian person in a room full

00:05:02.070 --> 00:05:03.680
of other authors.

00:05:03.680 --> 00:05:06.780
And I've liked being the
literary authorial person in a

00:05:06.780 --> 00:05:07.950
room full of comedians.

00:05:07.950 --> 00:05:09.020
I really enjoy it.

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:11.680
I like going between
different worlds.

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:16.190
I like trying to learn
everything about whatever

00:05:16.190 --> 00:05:18.440
world I'm in and mastering
it and trying to fit in.

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:20.800
I also like just being like,
whatever, I'm just here for

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:23.240
the day, and screwing around,
the way I maybe

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:25.580
am doing right now.

00:05:25.580 --> 00:05:28.030
And I love that.

00:05:28.030 --> 00:05:31.770
And the sort of interesting
thing about trying to pursue

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:35.320
multiple tracks at the same
time, or trying to be like a

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:37.560
polymath, if you want
to put it that way--

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:40.320
I do, because it sounds
awesome--

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:44.260
is not everybody wants
you to do that.

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:46.700
I feel like for the most part,
what people want you to do is

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:48.010
go, I am this.

00:05:48.010 --> 00:05:51.530
I am the best this
that there is.

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:53.250
But I've always kind of
preferred to be like, well,

00:05:53.250 --> 00:05:54.120
I'm a lot of things.

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:56.400
And if you encounter me
first doing one thing,

00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:57.970
hey, I also do this.

00:05:57.970 --> 00:06:00.610
And I can do all that
stuff, so I like

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:01.380
to do all that stuff.

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:04.580
And it's been a little bit of
a struggle, but I have found

00:06:04.580 --> 00:06:08.150
some synthesis with it in and
around my most recent book.

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:13.660
But I wanted really quickly
talk about kind of where I

00:06:13.660 --> 00:06:20.030
came from, which is a sketch
comedy background.

00:06:20.030 --> 00:06:22.970
I'm from Arizona originally,
but I went school at NYU,

00:06:22.970 --> 00:06:24.740
where I studied writing
for television.

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:27.720
And once there, I sort of fell
in with-- that makes it sound

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:28.110
like a gang.

00:06:28.110 --> 00:06:31.950
I fell in with some sketch
comedy bad boys.

00:06:31.950 --> 00:06:33.770
Not really, at all.

00:06:33.770 --> 00:06:37.330
But I started doing sketch
comedy, and that led me to the

00:06:37.330 --> 00:06:39.290
Upright Citizens Brigade
theater, where I learned

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:40.770
sketch and improv and stuff.

00:06:46.940 --> 00:06:49.430
I'm trying to think of the
best way to approach

00:06:49.430 --> 00:06:50.085
talking about it.

00:06:50.085 --> 00:06:53.420
So I was in a really large 15
person college sketch group.

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:59.140
And then a bunch of those people
graduated, and a couple

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:01.320
friends of mine and myself got
put in charge of our college

00:07:01.320 --> 00:07:01.980
sketch group.

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:06.120
And those guys were myself,
Donald Glover, who you may

00:07:06.120 --> 00:07:09.140
know, who's gone on to star in
"Community" and also raps

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:11.360
under the name Childish
Gambino.

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:13.120
There was one dude that just
got like 10 times more

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:14.340
interested, and I like that.

00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:16.280
He was like, oh, really,
OK, cool.

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:20.060
Put down my yam that
I'm chewing on.

00:07:20.060 --> 00:07:22.490
And another friend of mine named
Dominic Dierkes, and

00:07:22.490 --> 00:07:26.530
then a film director named Dan
Eckman, and a producer named

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:27.780
Meggie McFadden.

00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:35.210
First of all, myself, Dominic,
and Donald, we ended up

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:36.510
running this college
sketch group.

00:07:36.510 --> 00:07:40.070
We would put up these monthly
sketch shows, where the idea

00:07:40.070 --> 00:07:43.260
was hey, all these 10, 12 people
that are going to put

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:45.180
on this show, everybody's
going to write original

00:07:45.180 --> 00:07:47.120
material, we're all going to
band together and put on a

00:07:47.120 --> 00:07:50.770
show, like we're kids in an
after school special that are

00:07:50.770 --> 00:07:52.770
trying to save the teen
center, right?

00:07:52.770 --> 00:07:57.520
And the problem was that
everyone else in the group was

00:07:57.520 --> 00:07:58.620
all doing different things.

00:07:58.620 --> 00:07:59.760
They wanted to work
on their major.

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:02.490
They were like, I can't write a
sketch this month because I

00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:05.360
have to go be in a production
of "Pippin" that takes place

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:08.660
in space, so I can't
write anything.

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:10.760
So the three of us
would end up all

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:12.035
writing material together.

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:17.500
And I just realized I have
no way of knowing when

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:18.460
I'm going over time.

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:20.840
So Mike, if you could you give
me a light when I'm like half

00:08:20.840 --> 00:08:21.500
an hour in?

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:21.786
All right.

00:08:21.786 --> 00:08:21.930
Cool.

00:08:21.930 --> 00:08:22.910
And he's like, now.

00:08:22.910 --> 00:08:24.570
It's now.

00:08:24.570 --> 00:08:27.845
So we would end up writing a
bunch of material together,

00:08:27.845 --> 00:08:29.750
and it turned out we all really
liked each other's

00:08:29.750 --> 00:08:32.350
style, and liked each
other's vibe.

00:08:32.350 --> 00:08:35.640
I feel like I can use that word,
because we're in Venice.

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:39.440
And so the three of us plus
Dan and Meggie ended up

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:42.820
forming another sketch group
unto ourselves, where instead

00:08:42.820 --> 00:08:44.560
of performing stuff live--

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:48.240
because every time you do a
sketch live, you have to show

00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:50.760
up at the bar or whatever, and
like place all the wigs and

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:53.150
prop guns under all
the chairs--

00:08:53.150 --> 00:08:56.400
and we figured, let's just shoot
these sketches once, and

00:08:56.400 --> 00:08:58.370
then they can just kind
of exist forever.

00:08:58.370 --> 00:09:00.940
And this was around 2004.

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:04.070
And the most that we thought
could happened was, well,

00:09:04.070 --> 00:09:05.680
we'll put them on our own
personal website.

00:09:05.680 --> 00:09:08.020
We'll pay for hosting, and
there'll be a little QuickTime

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:08.530
that shows up.

00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:09.920
It'll take 12 minutes
to download.

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:16.020
Someone can watch this three
minute penis joke, and then

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:18.250
move on, and then maybe we'll
get to be on "MadTV," which

00:09:18.250 --> 00:09:20.110
was still a going concern
at the time.

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:25.130
And what ended up happening was
we shot a couple sketches,

00:09:25.130 --> 00:09:29.590
and we didn't have the money to
buy a server to host all of

00:09:29.590 --> 00:09:32.700
our three minute QuickTime
penis jokes.

00:09:32.700 --> 00:09:36.830
And the sketch "Lazy Sunday"
had just premiered on

00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:39.330
"Saturday Night Live."
And that was--

00:09:39.330 --> 00:09:41.890
maybe it's not the actual true
story, maybe like the literal

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:44.180
founder of YouTube is here,
and he'll disagree.

00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:44.910
He's probably not.

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:46.730
He's probably in space.

00:09:46.730 --> 00:09:50.320
But that sort of rocketed
YouTube

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:51.530
to prominence, weirdly.

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:53.490
The first time I ever heard
about YouTube was in

00:09:53.490 --> 00:09:56.760
connection with "Lazy Sunday,"
and this sketch that played on

00:09:56.760 --> 00:09:59.860
"Saturday Night Live" had had a
huge afterlife on this thing

00:09:59.860 --> 00:10:00.620
called YouTube.

00:10:00.620 --> 00:10:01.770
So I was like, oh, that
sounds interesting.

00:10:01.770 --> 00:10:04.020
So I went into my school's
computer lab.

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:05.750
I went onto YouTube.

00:10:05.750 --> 00:10:10.510
And I was like, I'll just upload
these sketches that I

00:10:10.510 --> 00:10:12.890
have in my email onto to this
thing called YouTube, and

00:10:12.890 --> 00:10:14.280
we'll just see what happens.

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:16.340
Because we don't have the
money to put them online

00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:19.660
ourselves, so this seems like
an easy enough workaround.

00:10:19.660 --> 00:10:22.080
And the name of our group was
Derrick, and I ended up making

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:26.970
our user name on YouTube Derrick
Comedy, and that ended

00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:28.500
up becoming the name
of our group.

00:10:28.500 --> 00:10:30.610
Which is a little bit weird--
it's like having music in the

00:10:30.610 --> 00:10:31.845
name of your brand.

00:10:31.845 --> 00:10:33.580
You're like, oh, comedy!

00:10:33.580 --> 00:10:34.810
It's a little bit obvious.

00:10:34.810 --> 00:10:39.380
But at the time, there was so
little on YouTube that wasn't

00:10:39.380 --> 00:10:42.680
just cats dancing.

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:46.320
It's still proportionally not
that much more than that.

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:49.920
But because I wanted to be
like this is comedy.

00:10:49.920 --> 00:10:52.120
What you're watching is people
trying to be funny.

00:10:52.120 --> 00:10:55.060
And even despite that, most of
our early videos, the first

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:57.990
comment on them would
always be-- fake!

00:10:57.990 --> 00:10:58.500
This is fake.

00:10:58.500 --> 00:10:59.470
It's like, yeah, it is fake.

00:10:59.470 --> 00:11:00.250
We made it.

00:11:00.250 --> 00:11:00.470
It's fake.

00:11:00.470 --> 00:11:00.860
You're right.

00:11:00.860 --> 00:11:02.375
You're correct.

00:11:02.375 --> 00:11:03.550
You can't fool me.

00:11:03.550 --> 00:11:05.800
It's like no, that's fine.

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:07.000
I hope you think it's fake.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.780
If you think it's real,
that's a problem.

00:11:10.780 --> 00:11:15.181
And so it ended up kind
of taking off.

00:11:15.181 --> 00:11:19.780
We had one sketch called
"Bro Rape," very cool--

00:11:19.780 --> 00:11:23.630
very cool thing to say in
a professional setting--

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:27.380
that ended up kind of getting a
really huge, I guess, viral

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:28.800
audience, if you want
to call it that.

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:31.370
And then from then on, a lot of
our sketches had a lot more

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:33.660
eyes on them.

00:11:33.660 --> 00:11:37.370
And instead of paying ourselves
with money that

00:11:37.370 --> 00:11:39.530
ended up coming in when YouTube
started doing revenue

00:11:39.530 --> 00:11:42.900
sharing, or from touring or
merchandising, which were also

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:45.680
things that we did with our
somewhat little slice of

00:11:45.680 --> 00:11:49.260
notoriety that we were carving
out, we decided to put all of

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:54.150
that money into an LLC and try
to save up to make something

00:11:54.150 --> 00:11:56.680
larger with it, like an
independent movie or a TV show

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:59.100
or something like that.

00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:02.570
And that seemed like a
really great idea.

00:12:02.570 --> 00:12:05.310
And then I graduated from
college, and I didn't have any

00:12:05.310 --> 00:12:06.000
money anymore.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:07.390
And then it was kind of like,
wait, so are we sure about

00:12:07.390 --> 00:12:08.120
this LLC thing?

00:12:08.120 --> 00:12:12.010
Because I could kind of use,
like, rent and pizza.

00:12:12.010 --> 00:12:18.380
But so being in that college
sketch group and then going on

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:20.130
to being in Derrick--

00:12:20.130 --> 00:12:23.590
and we made a movie, I'll talk
about it in a second--

00:12:23.590 --> 00:12:27.310
I sort of learned a couple
things that I'm still eating

00:12:27.310 --> 00:12:31.730
off of to this day,
or thinking about.

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:35.740
And the first one was when I was
still in college, and my

00:12:35.740 --> 00:12:38.220
friend Donald was still in
college or whatever.

00:12:38.220 --> 00:12:41.780
He is now a very
famous rapper.

00:12:41.780 --> 00:12:45.460
He was just nominated in the
same category as Jay-Z and

00:12:45.460 --> 00:12:47.670
Kanye West at the MTV
VMAs last year.

00:12:47.670 --> 00:12:51.780
At the time, he was just an RA
in his dorm who just made

00:12:51.780 --> 00:12:54.460
beats and raps on the side.

00:12:54.460 --> 00:12:56.170
And I sound like a dad
when I say that.

00:12:56.170 --> 00:12:58.710
He made some beats
and some raps.

00:12:58.710 --> 00:13:01.500
He turned the hip hop crank
and some raps came out.

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:02.180
It was great.

00:13:02.180 --> 00:13:04.030
That's good.

00:13:04.030 --> 00:13:05.280
Have an apple.

00:13:07.170 --> 00:13:13.000
But we would often talk about
the idea that we wanted to--

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:17.800
like, our dream in life was to
be able to just make your

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:20.130
whole culture.

00:13:20.130 --> 00:13:24.990
We liked the idea that us and
our friends would make enough

00:13:24.990 --> 00:13:29.900
stuff that a person could
conceivably live culturally in

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:32.200
terms of listening to music,
reading, watching movies,

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:35.140
watching TV shows, off just
the stuff that we made.

00:13:35.140 --> 00:13:39.450
And it's a super lofty goal,
but I still have that in my

00:13:39.450 --> 00:13:41.900
mind as what I would like to do
more than anything-- is be

00:13:41.900 --> 00:13:45.360
able to sustain someone, I don't
know for how long, but

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:47.730
through just what we do.

00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:51.990
And I still have that in my
head, even though it's a

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:53.260
little bit ridiculous.

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:54.750
And the other thing that I
noticed, and I was just

00:13:54.750 --> 00:13:56.170
thinking about this yesterday,
actually.

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:57.930
When I first got into that
sketch comedy group in

00:13:57.930 --> 00:13:59.040
college, and there
were 15 of us.

00:13:59.040 --> 00:13:59.790
We were all very excited.

00:13:59.790 --> 00:14:02.040
We were going to save
the teen center.

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:05.060
We would always talk about oh,
we should do a radio show.

00:14:05.060 --> 00:14:07.410
We should do puppets.

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:08.975
You know, I don't
know, whatever.

00:14:08.975 --> 00:14:10.480
Just all these different
pursuits that we

00:14:10.480 --> 00:14:11.270
really wanted to do.

00:14:11.270 --> 00:14:12.830
And this was my freshman year,
and I'm like, well, we'll have

00:14:12.830 --> 00:14:14.040
all this time this summer.

00:14:14.040 --> 00:14:15.320
We would always talk
about this summer.

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:16.100
We're going to do
it this summer.

00:14:16.100 --> 00:14:16.880
We have all this time.

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:18.360
And I'm sure you guys have
experienced the same thing,

00:14:18.360 --> 00:14:20.350
when you're working on a project
and you're like, oh, I

00:14:20.350 --> 00:14:21.830
had this other great idea
for this thing I

00:14:21.830 --> 00:14:24.270
really want to do.

00:14:24.270 --> 00:14:28.370
It's a comic strip about living
pastas or whatever.

00:14:28.370 --> 00:14:30.210
And you're like, I'm going to do
that as soon as this thing

00:14:30.210 --> 00:14:33.850
is done, and I just have this
huge vista of time.

00:14:33.850 --> 00:14:36.040
Well, what ended up happening,
as I'm sure you've experienced

00:14:36.040 --> 00:14:39.990
as well, is that vista of
totally unencumbered time

00:14:39.990 --> 00:14:41.120
never actually came.

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:43.470
It would always be the next
thing that we had to do, that

00:14:43.470 --> 00:14:44.970
we had to keep working on.

00:14:44.970 --> 00:14:48.280
And that still is true for
me to this day, where I'm

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:50.840
convinced, OK, after I finish--
like my book comes

00:14:50.840 --> 00:14:53.320
out next week on Thursday, and
I have this foolish thing in

00:14:53.320 --> 00:14:56.040
my head, like after that
happens, then I'll just be

00:14:56.040 --> 00:14:57.750
free to just learn the guitar.

00:14:57.750 --> 00:14:59.440
Or whatever.

00:14:59.440 --> 00:15:01.370
Not that.

00:15:01.370 --> 00:15:06.570
And it never comes, that sort
of ethereal summer of

00:15:06.570 --> 00:15:09.520
unlimited creativity where
you're going to get a shack

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:11.730
and put a drum in it.

00:15:11.730 --> 00:15:13.090
Never actually happens.

00:15:13.090 --> 00:15:18.530
But I like to think that if you
kind of live a full sort

00:15:18.530 --> 00:15:22.440
of creative life, then you turn
around after a point and

00:15:22.440 --> 00:15:25.410
you realize that you've been
doing all that stuff the

00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:26.140
entire way along.

00:15:26.140 --> 00:15:28.800
It just didn't feel like that
perfect creative time of just

00:15:28.800 --> 00:15:33.800
letting your mind roam
free on a porch.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:36.680
And the final thing that I
kind of learned-- not the

00:15:36.680 --> 00:15:38.830
final thing in my presentation,
no-- but the

00:15:38.830 --> 00:15:41.720
final thing that I learned from
doing sketch and doing

00:15:41.720 --> 00:15:44.240
improv and doing all these
different things is--

00:15:44.240 --> 00:15:46.650
well, I didn't learn it from
this, but the first time I

00:15:46.650 --> 00:15:48.690
heard it was in a Lauryn
Hill song.

00:15:48.690 --> 00:15:50.130
I don't know if you guys are
Lauryn Hill fans, but she had

00:15:50.130 --> 00:15:52.580
a follow up single to her first
smash single, "Doo-Wop

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:57.880
(That Thing)," in which she said
everything is everything.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:15:59.660
That's the hook of the song--
everything is everything.

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:00.480
Right?

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:01.090
Yeah, it's good, right?

00:16:01.090 --> 00:16:01.380
Yeah.

00:16:01.380 --> 00:16:02.660
There's a cool video.

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:03.950
New York City's like a record.

00:16:03.950 --> 00:16:04.430
It's great.

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:07.870
You can watch it on
Vevo after this.

00:16:07.870 --> 00:16:09.260
Give her some ad money.

00:16:09.260 --> 00:16:11.370
Who knows what she'll
spend it on?

00:16:11.370 --> 00:16:14.710
She's going to be so
mad at me for that.

00:16:14.710 --> 00:16:18.400
But I first heard that song,
and it's a good song, but I

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:20.430
was like, that's such a silly,
meaningless thing.

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:21.640
Everything is everything.

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:26.010
That's such a silly sort of like
weird fake zen BS thing.

00:16:26.010 --> 00:16:29.460
And what I realized through
doing sketch and doing improv

00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:32.730
and then going out and trying
to do other things is that I

00:16:32.730 --> 00:16:35.360
had already kind of in a weird
way learned not literally

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:37.920
everything I needed to know, but
a lot of what I needed to

00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:40.630
know by learning how to do
sketch, learning how to do

00:16:40.630 --> 00:16:41.710
improv, whatever.

00:16:41.710 --> 00:16:43.940
Everything really
was everything.

00:16:43.940 --> 00:16:48.720
I learned how to write like
children's TV and late night

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:51.440
jokes in college.

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:53.150
Because it wasn't
a real college.

00:16:53.150 --> 00:16:59.690
And when I sat down to
write my first book--

00:16:59.690 --> 00:17:02.030
this is what a book is--

00:17:02.030 --> 00:17:06.920
I realized all of those skills
that I had learned trying to

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:11.160
write that "Law and Order:
Criminal Intent" spec scripts

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:14.060
were really helping
me write this big

00:17:14.060 --> 00:17:17.020
work of literary fiction.

00:17:17.020 --> 00:17:22.849
When we went to make our first
feature film, "Mystery Team"

00:17:22.849 --> 00:17:25.700
the fact that we had been
studying how to write sketch

00:17:25.700 --> 00:17:30.240
helped us know how to write a
movie in terms of what to do,

00:17:30.240 --> 00:17:32.760
but also in terms of what not
to do, because a sketch is

00:17:32.760 --> 00:17:33.960
different than a movie.

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:36.500
So the best thing I feel like
you can do if you want to

00:17:36.500 --> 00:17:39.520
learn one thing is to learn
about anything,

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:40.880
because it all applies.

00:17:40.880 --> 00:17:43.140
And that sounds very--

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:44.975
first of all, I'm certainly not
the first person to say

00:17:44.975 --> 00:17:49.350
it, but it sounds very kind of
zen and hippie-ish and vibey.

00:17:49.350 --> 00:17:53.150
But it really has been true.

00:17:53.150 --> 00:17:54.510
It has proven true for me.

00:17:54.510 --> 00:17:56.770
Everything really
is everything.

00:17:56.770 --> 00:17:58.600
And I don't know.

00:17:58.600 --> 00:18:00.770
Lauryn Hill is right
about everything.

00:18:00.770 --> 00:18:03.090
Except for white people.

00:18:03.090 --> 00:18:05.980
We're cool.

00:18:05.980 --> 00:18:06.640
Let's see here.

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:08.910
I have a lot of cards that I
decided at a certain point to

00:18:08.910 --> 00:18:09.660
stop flipping through.

00:18:09.660 --> 00:18:12.160
Oh, yeah.

00:18:12.160 --> 00:18:13.580
So I graduated from college.

00:18:13.580 --> 00:18:17.380
And all throughout college, I
would go into the computer lab

00:18:17.380 --> 00:18:19.070
really late at night, and rather
than working on the

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:20.920
work I was supposed to be
working on, I would just end

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:23.430
up writing short stories
or little

00:18:23.430 --> 00:18:24.890
comedy pieces or whatever.

00:18:24.890 --> 00:18:29.160
Because as I'm sure you well
know, the best time to get

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:31.640
anything done is to
have another thing

00:18:31.640 --> 00:18:32.860
you're supposed to do.

00:18:32.860 --> 00:18:35.000
And then you'll just be like
yeah, my living room is so

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.315
clean now or whatever.

00:18:40.770 --> 00:18:42.240
And I would post them
on my website.

00:18:42.240 --> 00:18:44.870
And I always felt a little bit
weird about telling comedy

00:18:44.870 --> 00:18:45.750
friends of mine about them.

00:18:45.750 --> 00:18:48.355
Because when you think of
comedians, you think they're

00:18:48.355 --> 00:18:53.370
going to be like, hur, hur,
nice short story, dick.

00:18:53.370 --> 00:18:54.730
Actually, I think I'm
thinking of Biff.

00:18:58.290 --> 00:19:01.960
But people started finding my
website, and friends of mine.

00:19:01.960 --> 00:19:03.820
And then one day I was on the
subway, and I was coming in

00:19:03.820 --> 00:19:06.580
from Queens, and I saw
my friend Eliza.

00:19:06.580 --> 00:19:09.740
And she was like, I really like
these short stories you

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:11.140
write on your website.

00:19:11.140 --> 00:19:11.680
I was like, oh, thank you.

00:19:11.680 --> 00:19:13.170
She was like, you should
write a novel.

00:19:13.170 --> 00:19:14.330
And I was like, oh,
I would really

00:19:14.330 --> 00:19:14.960
like to do that someday.

00:19:14.960 --> 00:19:16.040
That would be something
I would like

00:19:16.040 --> 00:19:17.850
to do at some point.

00:19:17.850 --> 00:19:20.020
And she got really serious.

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:21.810
And it wasn't actually
happening, because it couldn't

00:19:21.810 --> 00:19:22.670
really happen on the subway.

00:19:22.670 --> 00:19:23.330
There are no windows.

00:19:23.330 --> 00:19:25.540
But in my memory, the wind
started blowing through her

00:19:25.540 --> 00:19:26.760
hair-- you know what I mean?

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:30.970
And she was like, a lot of
people say that, but not a lot

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:32.520
of people ever do it.

00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:35.170
And then again, in my memory,
she then blew away in the wind

00:19:35.170 --> 00:19:39.570
like sand, but she actually
just got off at a stop.

00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:42.010
But that was the effect that it
had on me, was of somebody

00:19:42.010 --> 00:19:43.970
who would then disappear
or whatever.

00:19:43.970 --> 00:19:52.615
And at the time, I was temping
in the accounting department

00:19:52.615 --> 00:19:55.420
at barnesandnoble.com.

00:19:55.420 --> 00:19:56.310
RIP.

00:19:56.310 --> 00:19:59.840
No, that's Borders, sorry.

00:19:59.840 --> 00:20:01.380
Barnes and Noble is
still going great.

00:20:01.380 --> 00:20:01.950
Go to their website.

00:20:01.950 --> 00:20:04.890
Anyway, you have to suck up to
booksellers, I guess, when

00:20:04.890 --> 00:20:07.230
you're an author.

00:20:07.230 --> 00:20:10.430
But so I was working in their
accounting department.

00:20:10.430 --> 00:20:13.530
And I was like, I'm on the
wrong side of books.

00:20:13.530 --> 00:20:14.780
I want to be writing
something bigger.

00:20:14.780 --> 00:20:15.240
She was right.

00:20:15.240 --> 00:20:15.970
A lot of people say it.

00:20:15.970 --> 00:20:17.650
Not a lot of people
ever do it.

00:20:17.650 --> 00:20:21.390
And as I've come to learn, my
great motivators are guilt and

00:20:21.390 --> 00:20:25.200
fear and shame and competition,
not really like

00:20:25.200 --> 00:20:27.090
inspiration and what they're
supposed to be, the higher

00:20:27.090 --> 00:20:27.670
minded things.

00:20:27.670 --> 00:20:29.900
It usually comes from somebody
being like, you can't do it.

00:20:29.900 --> 00:20:32.990
And I'll be like, I'll
show you, dad.

00:20:32.990 --> 00:20:39.500
So I told Eliza, I was
like, hey, I will--

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:40.460
I got so much louder.

00:20:40.460 --> 00:20:41.230
Did you guys hear that?

00:20:41.230 --> 00:20:42.350
Is that maybe because
I turned this way?

00:20:42.350 --> 00:20:42.580
I don't know.

00:20:42.580 --> 00:20:43.210
Yeah, you're right.

00:20:43.210 --> 00:20:45.280
Fair enough.

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:49.930
So I told Eliza, I was
like, hey, I'm

00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:51.520
going to write a book.

00:20:51.520 --> 00:20:52.580
I think I'm going
to write a book.

00:20:52.580 --> 00:20:56.020
But I need you to every time
you see me just like bug me

00:20:56.020 --> 00:20:59.150
about it-- just be like,
where's the book?

00:20:59.150 --> 00:21:00.170
Where is it?

00:21:00.170 --> 00:21:00.910
Hand over the book.

00:21:00.910 --> 00:21:02.150
You know what I mean?

00:21:02.150 --> 00:21:06.250
And I sort of made her into
my own mob enforcer of

00:21:06.250 --> 00:21:07.150
motivation.

00:21:07.150 --> 00:21:08.140
And she did it.

00:21:08.140 --> 00:21:09.240
Every time she saw me, she
was like, where is it?

00:21:09.240 --> 00:21:09.630
Where's the book?

00:21:09.630 --> 00:21:12.120
And I was like, I'm trying.

00:21:12.120 --> 00:21:14.990
So I quit my temp job at
barnesandnoble.com, and I

00:21:14.990 --> 00:21:16.410
didn't have any money.

00:21:16.410 --> 00:21:19.640
And then I booked one little
tiny web commercial that

00:21:19.640 --> 00:21:21.660
allowed me to then have
like a month off

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:22.830
just strictly to write.

00:21:22.830 --> 00:21:24.840
And then that sort of
kept happening.

00:21:24.840 --> 00:21:28.050
Because I had been an
improviser, and I worked at

00:21:28.050 --> 00:21:30.340
the Upright Citizens Brigade,
I had ended up getting a

00:21:30.340 --> 00:21:32.180
commercial agent, because
I bartended there.

00:21:32.180 --> 00:21:34.250
And then the fact that I had a
commercial agent meant I kept

00:21:34.250 --> 00:21:38.950
going out for commercials, and I
would book just one thing at

00:21:38.950 --> 00:21:45.930
the totally right interval to
not be entirely broke, and I

00:21:45.930 --> 00:21:46.900
could actually write.

00:21:46.900 --> 00:21:50.530
I could do it for my
job, basically,

00:21:50.530 --> 00:21:52.390
and work for myself.

00:21:52.390 --> 00:21:55.150
And I would not have been able
to do that otherwise.

00:21:55.150 --> 00:22:02.870
So I finished the book, and
I sent it to my agent.

00:22:02.870 --> 00:22:04.700
I didn't have a literary agent,
like somebody who could

00:22:04.700 --> 00:22:05.470
go and sell a book.

00:22:05.470 --> 00:22:08.530
I sent it to my acting agent
that I had gotten because me

00:22:08.530 --> 00:22:10.630
and my friends made
popular dick joke

00:22:10.630 --> 00:22:12.660
videos on the internet.

00:22:12.660 --> 00:22:14.830
And she read the manuscript,
and she was like,

00:22:14.830 --> 00:22:15.430
I really like this.

00:22:15.430 --> 00:22:16.850
I have a friend who's
a literary agent.

00:22:16.850 --> 00:22:19.320
I'll send it to him, and we'll
see what he thinks.

00:22:19.320 --> 00:22:20.600
So she sent it to him.

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:21.060
He called me.

00:22:21.060 --> 00:22:22.130
He was like, I really
like this book.

00:22:22.130 --> 00:22:23.260
I want to represent it.

00:22:23.260 --> 00:22:26.410
He sent it out to like nine
different publishing houses.

00:22:26.410 --> 00:22:29.360
Eight of them said no, and
one of them said yes.

00:22:29.360 --> 00:22:33.770
And I took the train in-- the
same train I'd met Eliza on--

00:22:33.770 --> 00:22:35.680
to go and meet my editor.

00:22:35.680 --> 00:22:37.900
And I was like, man, when I walk
through those doors, I'm

00:22:37.900 --> 00:22:40.050
not going to be dick
joke college

00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:41.450
sketch group DC Pierson.

00:22:41.450 --> 00:22:46.590
I'm going to be like august
literary specimen, future

00:22:46.590 --> 00:22:51.950
Pulitzer Prize winner, "New York
Times" weekend magazine

00:22:51.950 --> 00:22:56.780
interview having, literary
DC Pierson.

00:22:56.780 --> 00:22:59.650
And I walked through the
doors, and I go up,

00:22:59.650 --> 00:23:00.710
and I meet my editor.

00:23:00.710 --> 00:23:03.230
He's a guy named Jerry Howard.

00:23:03.230 --> 00:23:04.560
He's been around forever.

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:08.270
He's super kind of tweedy and
literary and old school.

00:23:08.270 --> 00:23:10.910
He's a person who you feel like
they're on Cape Cod even

00:23:10.910 --> 00:23:13.370
when they're not, they're
right there in front

00:23:13.370 --> 00:23:15.220
of you in New York.

00:23:15.220 --> 00:23:17.640
He did David Foster Wallace's
first book.

00:23:17.640 --> 00:23:20.480
He edited Bret Easton
