00:25:03.430 --> 00:25:05.380
And I was like, does
it matter for what?

00:25:05.380 --> 00:25:07.110
And he was like, not at all.

00:25:07.110 --> 00:25:11.640
He was telling me I could be
early Lindsay Lohan if I

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:13.660
wanted to and get famous for
being good at acting, or I

00:25:13.660 --> 00:25:16.400
could be late period Lindsay
Lohan and get famous for

00:25:16.400 --> 00:25:21.320
crashing a vodka truck into
another vodka truck.

00:25:24.130 --> 00:25:27.280
And I was like, OK,
cool, I'll do it.

00:25:27.280 --> 00:25:28.610
I'll try to get famous.

00:25:28.610 --> 00:25:31.740
So right around that time, my
friends and I in Derrick had

00:25:31.740 --> 00:25:34.530
shot our first movie, "Mystery
Team," which we financed

00:25:34.530 --> 00:25:37.160
through all that money that
we put into the LLC and I

00:25:37.160 --> 00:25:40.700
therefore didn't get to spend
on rent and pizza, and also

00:25:40.700 --> 00:25:48.240
some friends and family money
that they are slowly, slowly,

00:25:48.240 --> 00:25:49.890
slowly getting back.

00:25:49.890 --> 00:25:57.490
And we made our first feature
film, "Myster Team." And it

00:25:57.490 --> 00:25:58.930
went to Sundance.

00:25:58.930 --> 00:26:05.690
And it was an interesting time,
because it was the just

00:26:05.690 --> 00:26:09.660
perfect, perfect asshole
of the recession.

00:26:09.660 --> 00:26:11.390
Just right in there.

00:26:11.390 --> 00:26:14.120
Again, a really fun thing
to say in a workplace.

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:16.470
And nobody was buying movies.

00:26:16.470 --> 00:26:19.160
And our movie in particular
was sort of a hard sell

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:22.870
because instead of, again, a
movie about a filmmaker or

00:26:22.870 --> 00:26:27.600
whatever people buy at Sundance,
our movie was about

00:26:27.600 --> 00:26:34.030
three sort of Encyclopedia Brown
style G rated aw shucks

00:26:34.030 --> 00:26:38.720
detective kids having to solve
an R rated adult murder, and

00:26:38.720 --> 00:26:41.150
then being sucked into a world
of crime and drugs

00:26:41.150 --> 00:26:43.330
and boobs and stuff.

00:26:43.330 --> 00:26:50.190
And so the movie didn't
sell at Sundance.

00:26:50.190 --> 00:26:53.580
And people would continually
ask us about the movie when

00:26:53.580 --> 00:26:56.000
sort of trying to tell us why
they weren't going to buy it

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:01.940
and release it on 50,000 screens
was, well, why is it

00:27:01.940 --> 00:27:05.810
the G rated characters
in the R rated world?

00:27:05.810 --> 00:27:07.500
If it were just a G rated
thing, then that we get.

00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:08.270
That's a G rated movie.

00:27:08.270 --> 00:27:10.340
And if it were just an R rated
thing, that we understand,

00:27:10.340 --> 00:27:11.520
because then it's R rated.

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:12.535
But the G to the--

00:27:12.535 --> 00:27:13.540
And we were like, well,
that's the whole

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:15.260
premise of the movie.

00:27:15.260 --> 00:27:16.902
That's what's funny
about it to us.

00:27:16.902 --> 00:27:18.660
That's the whole idea.

00:27:18.660 --> 00:27:21.630
It would be like if somebody was
like, OK, so "Star Wars."

00:27:21.630 --> 00:27:24.260
We get Luke on the planet
at the beginning

00:27:24.260 --> 00:27:25.330
on this home world.

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:26.740
We get that, that totally
makes sense.

00:27:26.740 --> 00:27:28.120
And then we get the
stuff in space.

00:27:28.120 --> 00:27:30.710
But why in the same movie?

00:27:30.710 --> 00:27:31.910
It's like, because
that's the movie.

00:27:31.910 --> 00:27:35.200
That's "Star Wars." That's the
whole premise, being on this

00:27:35.200 --> 00:27:37.780
one world, and then going off
and having an adventure.

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:40.140
That's the whole what
makes it, it.

00:27:40.140 --> 00:27:43.470
And they were like, hmm, bye.

00:27:43.470 --> 00:27:46.130
And they pulled away.

00:27:46.130 --> 00:27:49.050
And so the movie did end
up selling, finally.

00:27:49.050 --> 00:27:51.540
We took it out here to LA and
back and forth to New York,

00:27:51.540 --> 00:27:54.220
and it ended up getting
distributed.

00:27:54.220 --> 00:27:57.970
And we, in conjunction with
our distributor, kind of

00:27:57.970 --> 00:28:01.700
developed this very
unconventional plan.

00:28:01.700 --> 00:28:04.370
And when people have money
and they hear the word

00:28:04.370 --> 00:28:07.150
unconventional, they start
to get really gun shy.

00:28:07.150 --> 00:28:08.540
And there's a reason they do.

00:28:08.540 --> 00:28:10.880
It's because mostly conventions
are conventions

00:28:10.880 --> 00:28:12.150
for a reason, because
they work.

00:28:12.150 --> 00:28:14.770
We were doing something
unconventional, and it had

00:28:14.770 --> 00:28:15.580
mixed results.

00:28:15.580 --> 00:28:17.750
We toured with our movie
in all these

00:28:17.750 --> 00:28:18.560
different college towns.

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:20.130
Because we're popular
in colleges.

00:28:20.130 --> 00:28:21.980
We make dick joke videos.

00:28:21.980 --> 00:28:23.720
People will love us
in college towns.

00:28:23.720 --> 00:28:26.550
We'll just put ourselves out
there, and then people will

00:28:26.550 --> 00:28:27.430
come in droves.

00:28:27.430 --> 00:28:28.030
Dick jokes!

00:28:28.030 --> 00:28:28.500
Dick jokes!

00:28:28.500 --> 00:28:31.650
That's what they'll chant.

00:28:31.650 --> 00:28:36.530
And so we went to towns like
Iowa City, Iowa, Ames,

00:28:36.530 --> 00:28:38.920
Tallahassee, Gainesville,
Florida.

00:28:38.920 --> 00:28:41.980
And all throughout that entire
time, what we ended up

00:28:41.980 --> 00:28:47.570
experiencing was very, very,
very empty auditoriums for the

00:28:47.570 --> 00:28:50.530
most part, but there would be
like three die hard kids in

00:28:50.530 --> 00:28:52.670
the front row that were so
excited to be there.

00:28:52.670 --> 00:28:54.520
And then we would do a Q&amp;A after
the movie, and then we

00:28:54.520 --> 00:28:55.630
would sign posters.

00:28:55.630 --> 00:28:58.160
And I swear to God, in one of
the first towns that we were

00:28:58.160 --> 00:29:00.110
in in Florida, the first kid
that came up to the table to

00:29:00.110 --> 00:29:02.320
get his poster signed
was like, what are

00:29:02.320 --> 00:29:04.190
you guys doing here?

00:29:04.190 --> 00:29:06.130
Not in a way of, like, sweet,
but in a way of,

00:29:06.130 --> 00:29:07.510
like, are you OK?

00:29:07.510 --> 00:29:11.450
What has happened that you are
in Gainesville at this AMC

00:29:11.450 --> 00:29:13.880
multiplex where all the
other movies have

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:16.410
$100 million budgets?

00:29:16.410 --> 00:29:19.230
And the answer was,
we don't know.

00:29:19.230 --> 00:29:20.820
We don't know what
we're doing here.

00:29:20.820 --> 00:29:21.830
But aren't you happy
we're here?

00:29:21.830 --> 00:29:27.196
And he was like, it's more
disconcerting than anything.

00:29:27.196 --> 00:29:28.590
And no one knew we
were out there.

00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:32.010
It would be a little bit
different now, I feel like,

00:29:32.010 --> 00:29:33.780
because Twitter is a little more
prominent or whatever,

00:29:33.780 --> 00:29:35.440
there is a little more of a
precedent of like, I'm in your

00:29:35.440 --> 00:29:36.510
town, show up.

00:29:36.510 --> 00:29:37.200
But maybe not.

00:29:37.200 --> 00:29:38.320
It might have just been
the same thing.

00:29:38.320 --> 00:29:41.950
So we kind of had to just get
our Henry Rollins on and just

00:29:41.950 --> 00:29:43.930
kind of make it happen
somehow.

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:46.090
So the fifth town that we went
to was a place called

00:29:46.090 --> 00:29:49.030
Columbia, Missouri, which is
an awesome college town.

00:29:49.030 --> 00:29:50.890
I highly recommend it if you
guys are thinking of going

00:29:50.890 --> 00:29:54.750
back to undergrad, journalism
school, or whatever.

00:29:54.750 --> 00:29:56.920
And we were there, and it
was the same thing.

00:29:56.920 --> 00:29:59.060
We were playing to like
three kids that were

00:29:59.060 --> 00:30:01.490
like, why are you here?

00:30:01.490 --> 00:30:04.310
Your parents are worried
about you.

00:30:04.310 --> 00:30:06.680
And I was like, we've
got to do something.

00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:12.350
So I had been going to Targets
and stuff before doing Q&amp;As,

00:30:12.350 --> 00:30:15.420
because I was like, there's
three kids here.

00:30:15.420 --> 00:30:17.630
We've got to give them something
for being the only

00:30:17.630 --> 00:30:20.200
ones that are remotely active
enough to find out

00:30:20.200 --> 00:30:21.230
that we're even here.

00:30:21.230 --> 00:30:24.450
So I would get them like
toy dinosaurs and weird

00:30:24.450 --> 00:30:25.910
foam bats and stuff.

00:30:25.910 --> 00:30:28.050
And then we were in Columbia,
and things

00:30:28.050 --> 00:30:29.060
were not going well.

00:30:29.060 --> 00:30:30.830
And we were at Walmart.

00:30:30.830 --> 00:30:31.770
Don't judge me.

00:30:31.770 --> 00:30:35.810
It's the only store in
a lot of places.

00:30:35.810 --> 00:30:36.940
And I was like, what
can we do?

00:30:36.940 --> 00:30:37.480
What can we do?

00:30:37.480 --> 00:30:40.740
And I just saw this bin
of foam swords.

00:30:40.740 --> 00:30:42.730
I was like, swords.

00:30:42.730 --> 00:30:44.350
It's got to be swords.

00:30:44.350 --> 00:30:47.560
So what we started doing to try
to build an audience in

00:30:47.560 --> 00:30:49.810
this town that we were going
to be in for a week and

00:30:49.810 --> 00:30:52.630
playing in for a week is we
would tell the people that

00:30:52.630 --> 00:30:56.460
came to the movie, hey, if you
come tomorrow, you're going to

00:30:56.460 --> 00:30:58.100
join Sword Club.

00:30:58.100 --> 00:30:59.220
And they were like,
what's Sword Club?

00:30:59.220 --> 00:31:03.650
And I was like, we'll give you
a sword, and it'll be hand

00:31:03.650 --> 00:31:07.360
numbered, unique to you,
with an inspirational

00:31:07.360 --> 00:31:09.110
quote written on it.

00:31:09.110 --> 00:31:10.700
And they were like,
all right, man.

00:31:10.700 --> 00:31:11.830
And they showed up
the next day.

00:31:11.830 --> 00:31:13.050
They usually brought friends.

00:31:13.050 --> 00:31:14.840
Because it was like, why are you
going back to that movie?

00:31:14.840 --> 00:31:15.680
He was like, Sword Club, man.

00:31:15.680 --> 00:31:19.010
And then the friend
wants to go.

00:31:19.010 --> 00:31:21.760
Before we went out on the road,
a friend of mine, this

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:24.390
guy named Todd Sklar, who's a
really cool filmmaker and a

00:31:24.390 --> 00:31:27.400
guy that also founded a company
that tours with little

00:31:27.400 --> 00:31:31.520
independent movies to colleges,
strictly because he

00:31:31.520 --> 00:31:33.600
wanted to get his first movie
that he made seen, and there

00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:36.870
was no other way to do, he was
like, your main competition

00:31:36.870 --> 00:31:38.380
when you go into these college
towns, your main

00:31:38.380 --> 00:31:41.610
competition is not--

00:31:41.610 --> 00:31:42.610
it's not even football.

00:31:42.610 --> 00:31:44.520
It's not them going to
see another movie.

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:46.650
Your main competition is people
staying in their house

00:31:46.650 --> 00:31:50.010
and getting high and
eating doughnuts.

00:31:50.010 --> 00:31:51.790
And he was right.

00:31:51.790 --> 00:31:53.065
And the doughnuts
were winning.

00:31:56.150 --> 00:31:59.620
So that was the impetus of Sword
Club, was to beat back

00:31:59.620 --> 00:32:01.270
with foam swords
from Walmart--

00:32:01.270 --> 00:32:03.320
again, that's the only place
that they sell these

00:32:03.320 --> 00:32:05.460
particular swords, and they have
them in all Walmarts, and

00:32:05.460 --> 00:32:06.450
they're great.

00:32:06.450 --> 00:32:07.700
Great product.

00:32:10.230 --> 00:32:14.120
We beat back the weed and the
doughnuts in Columbia.

00:32:14.120 --> 00:32:15.100
People started coming.

00:32:15.100 --> 00:32:18.430
By the end of the week, we were
playing to full houses.

00:32:18.430 --> 00:32:20.120
Oh, the other thing that we
promised was that if you

00:32:20.120 --> 00:32:22.620
joined Sword Club, we'll take
your name and email address,

00:32:22.620 --> 00:32:25.200
and we'll put your name
